<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1" />
  <title>Training Big Models on Small Memories — Field Notes</title>
  <!-- Use the same typefaces and colours as the original fractal blog -->
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
  <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
  <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Newsreader:ital,opsz,wght@0,6..72,400;0,6..72,500;1,6..72,400;1,6..72,500&family=Geist:wght@400;500;600&family=Geist+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" media="print" onload="this.media='all'" />
  <noscript><link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Newsreader:ital,opsz,wght@0,6..72,400;0,6..72,500;1,6..72,400;1,6..72,500&family=Geist:wght@400;500;600&family=Geist+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" /></noscript>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="blog.css" />
  <meta name="description" content="A tour of modern techniques that make deep learning possible on hardware with limited memory: subset-based training, dynamic rotation, gradient accumulation, and distributed strategies." />
</head>
<body>
  <main id="main" class="main">
    <!-- Masthead -->
    <header class="hero col">
      <h1>Training Big Models on Small Memories</h1>
      <p class="sub">Memory‑efficient deep learning strategies for large datasets</p>
    </header>

    <!-- Narrative body -->
    <article class="body col">
      <!-- 1 -->
      <section id="s1">
        <span class="sec-num">01 — Why memory matters</span>
        <h2>The challenge of scale</h2>
        <p class="lead"><span class="dropcap">D</span>eep neural networks are voracious.  State‑of‑the‑art models can contain billions of parameters, and the datasets they learn from often number in the millions of examples.  When all of that data and all of those activations must reside in memory at once, even the largest GPUs quickly run out of room.  This has spurred a rich field of research into <strong>memory‑efficient training</strong> – techniques that allow us to train on large datasets with modest hardware.</p>
        <p>One of the simplest ideas is to <em>not</em> load all of the data at once.  By dividing the training set into manageable subsets and iterating over them, we can reduce memory requirements by orders of magnitude.  In fact, careful partitioning and rotation of subsets can achieve performance that matches (and sometimes exceeds) full‑dataset training while using only a fraction of the memory【690053325685588†L10-L19】.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- 2 -->
      <section id="s2">
        <span class="sec-num">02 — Subset training</span>
        <h2>Chunking data and dynamic rotation</h2>
        <p>The basic premise of subset training is simple: break your dataset into chunks that fit into memory, train on one chunk at a time, then move to the next.  Three flavours are commonly used: fixed‑size chunking (uniformly dividing the data), content‑aware chunking (preserving class or semantic structure), and hybrid schemes that adapt chunk boundaries to the data distribution【690053325685588†L22-L33】.</p>
        <p>While sequentially processing chunks dramatically reduces memory usage, it can starve the model of diversity if the same subset is used for too long.  Modern methods therefore employ <em>dynamic subset rotation</em> — switching which chunk is in memory as training evolves.  Research shows that keeping a small overlap (10–20%) between consecutive subsets provides a balance between stability and diversity【690053325685588†L52-L59】, and that curriculum‑based rotations (starting with simpler subsets and progressively introducing harder examples) accelerate early training【690053325685588†L70-L75】.</p>
        <figure class="fig reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <span class="fig-tag">Figure&nbsp;01</span>
            <div class="fig-svg-wrap">
              <img src="subset_rotation_diagram.png" alt="Circular diagram illustrating dynamic rotation between five data subsets" />
            </div>
          </div>
          <figcaption><span class="fc-num">Fig.&nbsp;1</span> <b>Dynamic subset rotation.</b> The dataset is partitioned into several subsets (<em>S<sub>1</sub>...S<sub>5</sub></em>).  At any moment only one subset resides in memory.  After a scheduled interval, the next subset is loaded, with a small portion of the previous subset retained to maintain diversity.  Over training, the rotation schedule cycles through the entire dataset.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <!-- 3 -->
      <section id="s3">
        <span class="sec-num">03 — Foundations and convergence</span>
        <h2>Why subsets converge</h2>
        <p>At first glance it may seem that training on only part of the data cannot possibly recover the same optimum as training on everything.  The key insight is that the stochastic gradient computed on a random subset is an <strong>unbiased estimator</strong> of the full gradient: on average it points in the same direction【690053325685588†L79-L87】.  Under appropriate regularity conditions, the expected gradient of the loss over a subset equals the true gradient of the empirical risk.</p>
        <p>Recent theoretical work provides precise convergence guarantees.  For convex objectives, subset‑based stochastic gradient descent (SGD) achieves linear convergence with better dependence on the condition number than classical analyses【690053325685588†L88-L94】.  In the more relevant non‑convex case of deep networks, the theory ensures convergence to stationary points and shows that subset training can find flatter minima with similar generalization as full‑dataset training【690053325685588†L95-L104】.  PAC‑Bayesian bounds even quantify the generalization gap in terms of the mutual information between subsets and learned parameters【690053325685588†L97-L103】.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- 4 -->
      <section id="s4">
        <span class="sec-num">04 — Gradient accumulation</span>
        <h2>Simulating large batches on small hardware</h2>
        <p>Another powerful technique is <strong>gradient accumulation</strong>.  Instead of processing an entire batch at once, we split it into several micro‑batches that fit comfortably in memory, run separate forward/backward passes, accumulate the gradients, and perform a single parameter update.  Mathematically, this yields the same update as a large batch of size <em>N</em>: &nbsp;θ<sub>t+1</sub> = θ<sub>t</sub> − η (1/ <em>N</em>) Σ∇L(B<sub>i</sub>)【690053325685588†L115-L122】.</p>
        <p>Gradient accumulation reduces peak memory usage by roughly 2–3× in typical scenarios and has enabled models like BERT‑large to be trained on GPUs with only 5&nbsp;GB of memory instead of 15&nbsp;GB【690053325685588†L123-L126】.  Implementation details matter: gradients must be scaled appropriately, especially when using mixed precision; clipping after accumulation prevents exploding gradients; and the number of accumulation steps should be chosen so that the effective batch size matches the target batch size【690053325685588†L127-L147】.</p>
        <figure class="fig reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <span class="fig-tag">Figure&nbsp;02</span>
            <div class="fig-svg-wrap">
              <img src="gradient_accumulation_diagram.png" alt="Diagram illustrating how gradients from multiple micro‑batches are accumulated before a weight update" />
            </div>
          </div>
          <figcaption><span class="fc-num">Fig.&nbsp;2</span> <b>Accumulating before updating.</b> Each micro‑batch fits in memory and produces its own gradient.  These gradients are accumulated (summed) and then normalised before a single weight update is applied.  The method emulates a large batch without requiring all samples to reside in memory simultaneously.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <!-- 5 -->
      <section id="s5">
        <span class="sec-num">05 — Parallel and distributed strategies</span>
        <h2>When a single device isn’t enough</h2>
        <p>For truly enormous models, no amount of clever batching can overcome the fundamental size of the network.  <strong>Model parallelism</strong> addresses this by splitting a network across multiple devices: <em>pipeline parallelism</em> assigns different layers to different devices, processing micro‑batches sequentially【690053325685588†L156-L162】; <em>tensor parallelism</em> distributes individual matrix multiplications or attention operations across devices for better utilisation【690053325685588†L163-L166】; and <em>3D parallelism</em> combines data, pipeline and tensor parallelism to scale beyond 100&nbsp;B parameters【690053325685588†L168-L169】.</p>
        <p>Efficient implementations such as DeepSpeed and FairScale achieve near‑linear scaling across thousands of GPUs through optimised communication patterns and memory management【690053325685588†L171-L173】.  Techniques like ZeRO (Zero Redundancy Optimiser) shard parameters, gradients and optimizer states across devices to further reduce memory requirements【690053325685588†L174-L176】.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- 6 -->
      <section id="s6">
        <span class="sec-num">06 — Comparing strategies</span>
        <h2>Memory savings at a glance</h2>
        <p>How do these methods stack up?  The bar chart below summarises the typical reduction in peak memory compared to naïve full‑dataset, full‑batch training.  Subset training can reduce memory demands by an order of magnitude (often 10× or better), gradient accumulation yields a 2–3× reduction, while model and distributed parallelism reduce the per‑device memory footprint by splitting computations across hardware.</p>
        <figure class="fig reveal">
          <div class="frame">
            <span class="fig-tag">Figure&nbsp;03</span>
            <div class="fig-svg-wrap">
              <img src="memory_bar_chart.png" alt="Bar chart comparing the relative memory usage of subset training, gradient accumulation, model parallelism and distributed training" />
            </div>
          </div>
          <figcaption><span class="fc-num">Fig.&nbsp;3</span> <b>Relative memory usage.</b> Each bar shows the fraction of memory consumed relative to naïve training (lower is better).  Subset training achieves the greatest savings, followed by gradient accumulation; model and distributed parallelism reduce the memory per device but require multiple devices.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <!-- 7 -->
      <section id="s7">
        <span class="sec-num">07 — Best practices</span>
        <h2>Putting it all together</h2>
        <p>Memory efficiency is rarely the result of a single trick.  Instead, practitioners combine subset training (with carefully tuned rotation schedules), gradient accumulation (with appropriate scaling and clipping) and, where budget allows, parallel and distributed execution.  Matching learning rates to the increased gradient variance is essential【690053325685588†L111-L114】; so is ensuring that each subset maintains sufficient diversity and that accumulation steps match the target batch size【690053325685588†L143-L147】.</p>
        <p>At a high level, the goal is to expose the model to as much of the dataset as possible while keeping only a small slice in memory.  Modern optimisers appear robust to such approximations, and theoretical guarantees show that, under reasonable conditions, memory‑efficient training converges to the same solutions as full‑dataset training【690053325685588†L79-L104】.</p>
      </section>
    </article>

    <!-- Takeaways box -->
    <div class="takeaways">
      <div class="takeaways-box reveal">
        <div class="lbl">Practical lessons</div>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Diversify your subsets.</strong> Use content‑aware or hybrid chunking and rotate with 10–20&nbsp;% overlap to avoid over‑fitting to a small slice of data【690053325685588†L52-L59】.</li>
          <li><strong>Accumulate wisely.</strong> Choose the number of micro‑batches such that the effective batch size matches your target and scale gradients appropriately【690053325685588†L115-L147】.</li>
          <li><strong>Scale across devices.</strong> When a single GPU isn’t enough, employ pipeline, tensor and data parallelism with sharded optimizers like ZeRO to distribute memory demands【690053325685588†L156-L176】.</li>
          <li><strong>Tune the learning rate.</strong> Increased gradient variance from subset training often calls for smaller or adaptive learning rates to ensure stable convergence【690053325685588†L111-L114】.</li>
          <li><strong>Mix and match.</strong> The most efficient pipelines combine all of the above – subsets, accumulation and parallelism – to train giant models on limited hardware.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- References -->
    <section class="refs reveal" aria-label="References">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref-1"><cite>Memory‑Efficient Deep Learning Training Strategies for Large Datasets.</cite> Detailed analysis of subset training, dynamic rotation and convergence guarantees【690053325685588†L10-L104】.</li>
        <li id="ref-2">IBM Research et&nbsp;al. <cite>Large‑Scale Subset Rotation for Efficient 8‑bit Training.</cite> Empirical study demonstrating 2–4× acceleration through chunk‑based accumulation【690053325685588†L34-L37】.</li>
        <li id="ref-3">Various authors. <cite>Gradient Accumulation for Memory‑Constrained Training.</cite> Technical reports outlining the mathematical equivalence of accumulation to large‑batch updates and practical recommendations【690053325685588†L115-L147】.</li>
        <li id="ref-4">DeepSpeed &amp; FairScale teams. <cite>Scaling Neural Network Training with 3D Parallelism and ZeRO.</cite> Documentation of pipeline, tensor and data parallel strategies with sharded optimizers【690053325685588†L156-L176】.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

